To create a basic search bar in PHP, you will need to have the following:

1. A form to input search queries.
2. A PHP script that processes the query and returns results (this example uses a simple echo statement for demonstration purposes).
3. An understanding of how to connect your PHP application with a database if you plan to search through database content.

Below is a basic example using HTML, CSS, and PHP. This example assumes you're running Apache, MySQL, and PHP locally.

**index.php**

```php
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <title>Search</title>
    <style>
        form {
            width: 300px;
            margin: auto;
        }

        input[type='text'] {
            padding: 10px;
            font-size: 16px;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
        }

        button[type='submit'] {
            background-color: #4CAF50;
            color: white;
            padding: 10px 20px;
            border: none;
            cursor: pointer;
        }
    </style>
</head>

<body>
<form action="" method="post">
    <input type="text" name="search_query" placeholder="Enter your search query here..."/>
    <button type="submit">Search</button>
</form>

<?php
// Check if the form has been submitted
if ($_SERVER["REQUEST_METHOD"] == "POST") {
    $searchQuery = $_POST['search_query'];
    echo "<h2>Searching for: \"$searchQuery\"</h2>";

    // To simulate results, we'll just echo a message here. In a real application,
    // you'd connect to your database and execute queries based on the search query.
    if ($searchQuery != '') {
        echo "Search results will appear here.";
    } else {
        echo "Please enter something in the search box.";
    }
}
?>
</body>
</html>
```

This basic example provides a form where you can input your search query. When submitted, it checks for a POST request and displays a message indicating what was searched for.

For a real-world application searching through database content, consider:

1. **Connect to Your Database**: Use PHP's PDO or MySQLi extension to connect to your database.
2. **Query the Database**: Based on user input, construct SQL queries dynamically to retrieve relevant data from your tables.
3. **Display Results**: Echo these results in a format that makes sense for your application.

**Security Note:** Always use prepared statements when constructing SQL queries from user input to prevent SQL injection attacks.

This example is simplified and does not include any error handling or security measures you would want to implement in a production environment.

